<font color="#FF0000">MAIA LIN  &amp; RACISM</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec 26 23:19:34 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The U.S. has been built on a racist philosophy since<br>
its beginning (and before). Land stolen from Native<br>
Americans, Slavery, Chineese forced Labor to build the <br>
Rail Roads, Internment camps, etc. etc.<br><br>
Today we see racism in atitudes and acations towards <br>
non-white people. We see Racism on the parts of non-<br>
Whites towards White people. Why should we think that<br>
it would not be present during the Vietnam War. I <br>
believe that war creates strange bed fellows. When <br>
your life depends on a unity of action with someone<br>
you tend to overlook their ethnicity. When troups<br>
returned from the war, the racism that was forgotten<br>
was remembered. Sometimes with less ferocity, but <br>
I believe that it was always there.<br><br>
I think that there are many aspect towards racism. As<br>
a society we have a strong foundation in racism. Most<br>
people are not racist, but some of the things they do<br>
are racist. The distiction is important, because it<br>
allows us to view our own actions with a critical eye,<br>
but not get into the unproductive guilt of being a <br>
&quot;racist&quot;.<br><br>
In the war, there was a dispropotionate number of blacks<br>
in the front lines, a disproportionate number of whites<br>
in command. Vietnamese were looked at as less than equal<br>
and this created the foundation for the dehumanization<br>
of the enemy and the ability for people to consider<br>
and perform atrocities.<br><br>
Jed <br><br>

